    "solution": "- **(2) Py write B1:** Py allocates+writes B1 ‚Üí M(1); nobody else had B1. Px keeps E(0), Pz keeps M(2). B1 now stale.\n- **(3) Px read B1:** Px evicts B0 (clean E, no write-back), loads B1; Py M(1) writes back ‚Üí both S(1), B1 up to date.\n- **(4) Pz read B1:** Pz evicts its **Modified** B2 ‚Üí **writes B2 back** (B2 now up to date), loads B1 ‚Üí all three S(1).\n- **(5) Pz write B1:** upgrade to M(1), invalidate Px, Py ‚Üí I. B1 stale; B2 stays up to date (no one holds it dirty now).\n- **(6) Px read B2:** Px (was Invalid) loads B2; nobody else has B2 ‚Üí E(2). Pz still M(1) so B1 remains stale.\n\nThe instructive step is **(4)**: reading a new block forces Pz to write back its dirty B2 first, which is why memory B2 flips to *up to date* even though the access targets B1.",
